--- !u!114 &-2201746703235901428
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 4639002202562267395}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: 'The Igbo-Ukwu shell vessel is a remarkable bronze artifact created
      by the Igbo-Ukwu civilization, which flourished in southeastern Nigeria around
      the 9th century CE. Discovered in a group of sacred ritual chambers, the vessel
      demonstrates an exceptionally advanced level of lost-wax bronze casting, making
      Igbo-Ukwu one of the earliest and most sophisticated metalworking cultures
      in Sub-Saharan Africa.


      The vessel is designed in the form of a large
      conch shell, complete with intricate spirals, ridges, and surface decorations
      that mirror natural marine forms. Its surface is richly embellished with geometric
      patterns, plaited motifs, and fine texturing, showcasing artistic precision
      far beyond what was typical for the period.


      Scholars believe the shell
      vessel served ceremonial or religious purposes, possibly linked to royal regalia,
      offerings, or ritual storage. The symbolism of the shell may reflect beliefs
      about fertility, water deities, or spiritual communication, themes common in
      Igbo cosmology.


      The Igbo-Ukwu discoveries, including the shell vessel,
      provide groundbreaking evidence of early long-distance trade, wealth accumulation,
      and high social complexity in West Africa. The vessel remains one of the finest
      examples of ancient African metalwork, celebrated for both its artistic beauty
      and technological innovation.'
